						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/Commodities/Livestock/Related-developments/Scottish-and-Kenyan-research-groups-collaborate-to-improve-control-of-deadly-cattle-disease-in-Africa" title="Scottish and Kenyan research groups collaborate to improve control of deadly cattle disease in Africa" alt="link">Scottish and Kenyan research groups collaborate to improve control of deadly cattle disease in Africa</a></h2>

	
					<p>Recent studies of East Coast fever have shown that the so-called ‘protective’ proteins of the causative parasite—that is, the antigenic molecules that are recognized by the T lymphocytes of the bovine immune system and thus help animals fight development of disease—vary among the different strains of the parasite that exist in the field. This project will build on these advances to investigate the nature and extent of variability in these antigens between parasite strains. This knowledge will help scientists understand the factors that determine which parasite strains induce protective immune responses in animals that have been vaccinated. Results of the project should provide methods for maintaining high quality of the current live vaccine and identifying parasite strains that could be incorporated into an improved second-generation live vaccine. (Source: ILRI, 17 February 2010)</p>
							<p><span class="date">2/03/2010</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/Commodities/Livestock/Related-developments/Scottish-and-Kenyan-research-groups-collaborate-to-improve-control-of-deadly-cattle-disease-in-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/Commodities/Livestock/Related-developments/African-livestock-can-triumph-in-the-face-of-climate-change" title="African livestock can triumph in the face of climate change" alt="link">African livestock can triumph in the face of climate change</a></h2>

	
					<p>Africa's livestock producers are proving resilient to climate change and generating huge economic benefits for their nations and regions, researchers said in a book published on the 31th of January by the International Institute for Environment and Development (IIED) and SOS Sahel. The book shows how pastoralism is a major economic player and contributor to many African economies and one whose importance is only set to grow as climate change takes hold. The book shows how livestock play a key role in the economic prosperity in African's drylands by supporting hundreds of millions of people, and a massive meat and leather industry. 'What is remarkable is that these benefits all arise from animals fed solely on natural pasture,' said Ced Hesse, a researcher at IIED and one of the book's authors. (Source: IIED, 3 February 2010)</p>
							<p><span class="date">1/03/2010</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/Commodities/Livestock/Related-developments/African-livestock-can-triumph-in-the-face-of-climate-change">Read more...</a>
</div>
